[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] The **Canvas API** provides a means for drawing graphics via JavaScript and the HTML `<canvas>` element.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] Among other things, it can be used for animation, game graphics, data visualization, photo manipulation, and real-time video processing.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] The Canvas API largely focuses on 2D graphics.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] The WebGL API, which also uses the `<canvas>` element, draws hardware-accelerated 2D and 3D graphics.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] This simple example draws a green rectangle onto a canvas.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] The `Document.getElementById()` method gets a reference to the HTML `<canvas>` element.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] Next, the `HTMLCanvasElement.getContext()` method gets that element's context—the thing onto which the drawing will be rendered.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] The actual drawing is done using the `CanvasRenderingContext2D` interface.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] The `fillStyle` property makes the rectangle green.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] The `fillRect()` method places its top-left corner at (10, 10), and gives it a size of 150 units wide by 100 tall.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] `CanvasCaptureMediaStreamTrack` is a related interface.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] A comprehensive tutorial covering both the basic usage of the Canvas API and its advanced features.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] A hands-on, book-length introduction to the Canvas API and WebGL.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] Combining `<video>` and `<canvas>` to manipulate video data in real time.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] The Canvas API is extremely powerful, but not always simple to use.
[src:canvas-api/api-canvas-api] The libraries listed below can make the creation of canvas-based projects faster and easier.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] Since we're using JavaScript to control `<canvas>` elements, it's also very easy to make (interactive) animations.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] In this chapter we will take a look at how to do some basic animations.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] Probably the biggest limitation is, that once a shape gets drawn, it stays that way.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] If we need to move it we have to redraw it and everything that was drawn before it.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] It takes a lot of time to redraw complex frames and the performance depends highly on the speed of the computer it's running on.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] **Save the canvas state** If you're changing any setting (such as styles, transformations, etc.) which affect the canvas state and you want to make sure the original state is used each time a frame is drawn, you need to save that original state.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] **Draw animated shapes** The step where you do the actual frame rendering.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] **Restore the canvas state** If you've saved the state, restore it before drawing a new frame.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] Shapes are drawn to the canvas by using the canvas methods directly or by calling custom functions.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] In normal circumstances, we only see these results appear on the canvas when the script finishes executing.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] For instance, it isn't possible to do an animation from within a `for` loop.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] That means we need a way to execute our drawing functions over a period of time.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] There are two ways to control an animation like this.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] First there's the `setInterval()`, `setTimeout()`, and `requestAnimationFrame()` functions, which can be used to call a specific function over a set period of time.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] Starts repeatedly executing the function specified by `function` every `delay` milliseconds.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] Executes the function specified by `function` in `delay` milliseconds.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] Tells the browser that you wish to perform an animation and requests that the browser call a specified function to update an animation before the next repaint.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] If you don't want any user interaction you can use the `setInterval()` function, which repeatedly executes the supplied code.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] If we wanted to make a game, we could use keyboard or mouse events to control the animation and use `setTimeout()`.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] By setting listeners using `addEventListener()`, we catch any user interaction and execute our animation functions.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] This example animates a small model of our solar system.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] This example draws an animated clock, showing your current time.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] In this example, a panorama is scrolled left-to-right.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] We're using an image of Yosemite National Park we took from Wikipedia, but you could use any image that's larger than the canvas.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] The HTML includes the `<canvas>` in which the image is scrolled.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] Note that the width and height specified here must match the values of the `canvasXSize` and `canvasYSize` variables in the JavaScript code.
[src:canvas-api/basic-animations] We will have a look at some advanced animation techniques and physics in the next chapter.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] The HTML **canvas element** allows for dynamic, scriptable rendering of 2D shapes and bitmap images.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Introduced in HTML5, it is a low level, procedural model that updates a bitmap.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] The `<canvas>` element also helps in making 2D games.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] While the `<canvas>` element offers its own 2D drawing API, it also supports the WebGL API to allow 3D rendering with OpenGL ES.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Canvas was initially introduced by Apple for use in their own Mac OS X WebKit component in 2004, powering applications like Dashboard widgets and the Safari browser.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Later, in 2005, it was adopted in version 1.8 of Gecko browsers, and Opera in 2006, and standardized by the Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group (WHATWG) on new proposed specifications for next generation web technologies.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] A `canvas` consists of a drawable region defined in HTML code with *height* and *width* attributes.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] JavaScript code may access the area through a full set of drawing functions similar to those of other common 2D APIs, thus allowing for dynamically generated graphics.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Some anticipated uses of canvas include building graphs, animations, games, and image composition.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Interacting with the canvas involves obtaining the canvas' rendering context, which determines whether to use the canvas API, WebGL, or WebGL2 rendering context.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] This code draws a red rectangle on the screen.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] The Canvas API also provides `save()` and `restore()`, for saving and restoring all the canvas context's attributes.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] A canvas actually has two sizes: the size of the element itself and the size of the element's drawing surface.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Setting the element's width and height attributes sets both of these sizes; CSS attributes affect only the element's size and not the drawing surface.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] By default, both the canvas element's size and the size of its drawing surface is 300 screen pixels wide and 150 screen pixels high.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] In the listing shown in the example, which uses CSS to set the canvas element's size, the size of the element is 600 pixels wide and 300 pixels high, but the size of the drawing surface remains unchanged at the default value of 300 pixels × 150 pixels.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] When a canvas element's size does not match the size of its drawing surface, the browser scales the drawing surface to fit the element (which may result in surprising and unwanted effects).
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] SVG is an alternative approach to drawing shapes in browsers.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Unlike canvas, which is raster-based, SVG is vector-based, so that each drawn shape is remembered as an object in a scene graph or Document Object Model, which is subsequently rendered to a bitmap.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] This means that if attributes of an SVG object are changed, the browser can automatically re-render the scene.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Canvas objects, on the other hand, are drawn in immediate mode.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] In the canvas example above, the rectangle draw operation modifies the canvas, and its representation as a rectangle is forgotten by the system.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] If the rectangle's position were to be changed, the canvas would need to be redrawn, including any objects that might have been covered by the rectangle.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] In the equivalent SVG case, one could simply change the position attributes of the rectangle and the browser would determine how to repaint it.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] There are additional JavaScript libraries that abstract the canvas model to have svg-like scene capabilities within the canvas element.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Multiple canvas layers can also be used, meaning that only specific layers need to be recreated when changes are required.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] SVG images are represented in XML, and complex scenes can be created and maintained with XML editing tools.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] The SVG scene graph enables event handlers to be associated with objects, so a rectangle may respond to an `onClick` event.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] To get the same functionality with canvas, one must manually match the coordinates of the mouse click with the coordinates of the drawn rectangle to determine whether it was clicked.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Conceptually, canvas is a lower-level API upon which higher-level interfaces might be built (for example, SVG support).
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] There are JavaScript libraries that provide partial SVG implementations using canvas for browsers that do not provide SVG but support canvas, such as the browsers in Android 2.x.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] However, this is not normally the case—they are independent standards.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] The situation is complicated because there are scene graph libraries for canvas, and SVG has some bitmap manipulation functionality.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] At the time of its introduction, the canvas element was met with mixed reactions from the web standards community.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] There have been arguments against Apple's decision to create a new proprietary element instead of supporting the SVG standard.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] There are other concerns about syntax, such as the absence of a namespace.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] This caused considerable discussion among web developers and raised questions concerning the WHATWG's lack of a policy on patents in comparison to the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C)'s explicit favoring of royalty-free licenses.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Apple later disclosed the patents under the W3C's royalty-free patent licensing terms.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] The disclosure means that Apple is required to provide royalty-free licensing for the patent whenever the Canvas element becomes part of a future W3C recommendation created by the HTML working group.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] Canvas fingerprinting is one of a number of browser fingerprinting techniques for tracking online users that allow websites to identify and track visitors using the HTML `<canvas>` element.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] The technique received wide media coverage in 2014, after researchers from Princeton University and KU Leuven University described it in their paper *The Web never forgets*.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] The privacy concerns regarding canvas fingerprinting center around the fact that even deleting cookies and clearing the cache will not be sufficient for users to avoid online tracking.
[src:canvas-api/canvas-element] The element is supported by the current versions of Mozilla Firefox, Google Chrome, Internet Explorer, Safari, Konqueror, Opera and Microsoft Edge.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The **`CanvasRenderingContext2D`** interface, part of the Canvas API, provides the 2D rendering context for the drawing surface of a `<canvas>` element.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] It is used for drawing shapes, text, images, and other objects.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The interface's properties and methods are described in the reference section of this page.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The Canvas tutorial has more explanation, examples, and resources, as well.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] For `OffscreenCanvas`, there is an equivalent interface that provides the rendering context.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The offscreen rendering context inherits most of the same properties and methods as the `CanvasRenderingContext2D` and is described in more detail in the `OffscreenCanvasRenderingContext2D` reference page.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] With the context in hand, you can draw anything you like.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Returns an object containing the context attributes used by the browser.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Context attributes can be requested when using `HTMLCanvasElement.getContext()` to create the 2D context.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Returns `true` if the rendering context was lost.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] There are three methods that immediately draw rectangles to the canvas.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Sets all pixels in the rectangle defined by starting point *(x, y)* and size *(width, height)* to transparent black, erasing any previously drawn content.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Draws a filled rectangle at *(x, y)* position whose size is determined by *width* and *height*.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Paints a rectangle which has a starting point at *(x, y)* and has a *w* width and an *h* height onto the canvas, using the current stroke style.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] See also the `TextMetrics` object for text properties.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Draws (fills) a given text at the given (x, y) position.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Draws (strokes) a given text at the given (x, y) position.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The following methods and properties control how lines are drawn.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `butt` (default), `round`, `square`.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Defines the type of corners where two lines meet.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `round`, `bevel`, `miter` (default).
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Returns the current line dash pattern array containing an even number of non-negative numbers.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Specifies where to start a dash array on a line.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The following properties control how text is laid out.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `start` (default), `end`, `left`, `right`, `center`.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `top`, `hanging`, `middle`, `alphabetic` (default), `ideographic`, `bottom`.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `ltr`, `rtl`, `inherit` (default).
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `auto` (default), `normal`, `none`.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `ultra-condensed`, `extra-condensed`, `condensed`, `semi-condensed`, `normal` (default), `semi-expanded`, `expanded`, `extra-expanded`, `ultra-expanded`.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `normal` (default), `small-caps`, `all-small-caps`, `petite-caps`, `all-petite-caps`, `unicase`, `titling-caps`.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `auto` (default), `optimizeSpeed`, `optimizeLegibility`, `geometricPrecision`.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Gets or sets the language of the canvas drawing context.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Fill styling is used for colors and styles inside shapes and stroke styling is used for the lines around shapes.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Color or style to use for the lines around shapes.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a conic gradient around a point given by coordinates represented by the parameters.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a linear gradient along the line given by the coordinates represented by the parameters.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a radial gradient given by the coordinates of the two circles represented by the parameters.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a pattern using the specified image.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] It repeats the source in the directions specified by the repetition argument.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Horizontal distance the shadow will be offset.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Vertical distance the shadow will be offset.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The following methods can be used to manipulate paths of objects.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Starts a new path by emptying the list of sub-paths.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Call this method when you want to create a new path.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Causes the point of the pen to move back to the start of the current sub-path.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] It tries to draw a straight line from the current point to the start.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] If the shape has already been closed or has only one point, this function does nothing.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Moves the starting point of a new sub-path to the (x, y) coordinates.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Connects the last point in the current sub-path to the specified (x, y) coordinates with a straight line.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a cubic Bézier curve to the current path.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a quadratic Bézier curve to the current path.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a circular arc to the current path.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds an arc to the current path with the given control points and radius, connected to the previous point by a straight line.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds an elliptical arc to the current path.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a path for a rectangle at position (x, y) with a size that is determined by *width* and *height*.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a path for a rounded rectangle with a specified position, width, height, and corner radii.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Fills the current sub-paths with the current fill style.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Strokes the current sub-paths with the current stroke style.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] If a given element is focused, this method draws a focus ring around the current path.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a clipping path from the current sub-paths.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Everything drawn after `clip()` is called appears inside the clipping path only.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] For an example, see Clipping paths in the Canvas tutorial.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Reports whether or not the specified point is contained in the current path.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Reports whether or not the specified point is inside the area contained by the stroking of a path.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Objects in the `CanvasRenderingContext2D` rendering context have a current transformation matrix and methods to manipulate it.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The transformation matrix is applied when creating the current default path, painting text, shapes and `Path2D` objects.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The methods listed below remain for historical and compatibility reasons as `DOMMatrix` objects are used in most parts of the API nowadays and will be used in the future instead.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Retrieves the current transformation matrix being applied to the context.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a rotation to the transformation matrix.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The angle argument represents a clockwise rotation angle and is expressed in radians.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a scaling transformation to the canvas units by x horizontally and by y vertically.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a translation transformation by moving the canvas and its origin x horizontally and y vertically on the grid.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Multiplies the current transformation matrix with the matrix described by its arguments.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Resets the current transform to the identity matrix, and then invokes the `transform()` method with the same arguments.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Resets the current transform by the identity matrix.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Alpha value that is applied to shapes and images before they are composited onto the canvas.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] With `globalAlpha` applied this sets how shapes and images are drawn onto the existing bitmap.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] This method is available in multiple formats, providing a great deal of flexibility in its use.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a new, blank `ImageData` object with the specified dimensions.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] All of the pixels in the new object are transparent black.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Returns an `ImageData` object representing the underlying pixel data for the area of the canvas denoted by the rectangle which starts at *(sx, sy)* and has an *sw* width and *sh* height.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Paints data from the given `ImageData` object onto the bitmap.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] If a dirty rectangle is provided, only the pixels from that rectangle are painted.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Image smoothing mode; if disabled, images will not be smoothed if scaled.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Allows you to set the quality of image smoothing.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The `CanvasRenderingContext2D` rendering context contains a variety of drawing style states (attributes for line styles, fill styles, shadow styles, text styles).
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Saves the current drawing style state using a stack so you can revert any change you make to it using `restore()`.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Restores the drawing style state to the last element on the 'state stack' saved by `save()`.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] A read-only back-reference to the `HTMLCanvasElement`.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Might be `null` if it is not associated with a `<canvas>` element.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Resets the rendering context, including the backing buffer, the drawing state stack, path, and styles.
[src:canvas-api/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Applies a CSS or SVG filter to the canvas, e.g., to change its brightness or blurriness.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Now that we have set up our canvas environment, we can get into the details of how to draw on the canvas.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] By the end of this article, you will have learned how to draw rectangles, triangles, lines, arcs and curves, providing familiarity with some of the basic shapes.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Working with paths is essential when drawing objects onto the canvas and we will see how that can be done.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Before we can start drawing, we need to talk about the canvas grid or **coordinate space**.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Our HTML skeleton from the previous page had a canvas element 150 pixels wide and 150 pixels high.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Normally 1 unit in the grid corresponds to 1 pixel on the canvas.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The origin of this grid is positioned in the *top left* corner at coordinate (0,0).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] All elements are placed relative to this origin.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] So the position of the top left corner of the blue square becomes x pixels from the left and y pixels from the top, at coordinate (x,y).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Later in this tutorial we'll see how we can translate the origin to a different position, rotate the grid and even scale it, but for now we'll stick to the default.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Unlike SVG, `<canvas>` only supports two primitive shapes: rectangles and paths (lists of points connected by lines).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] All other shapes must be created by combining one or more paths.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Luckily, we have an assortment of path drawing functions which make it possible to compose very complex shapes.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Clears the specified rectangular area, making it fully transparent.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Each of these three functions takes the same parameters.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] `x` and `y` specify the position on the canvas (relative to the origin) of the top-left corner of the rectangle.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] `width` and `height` provide the rectangle's size.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Below is the `draw()` function from the previous page, but now it is making use of these three functions.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The `fillRect()` function draws a large black square 100 pixels on each side.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The `clearRect()` function then erases a 60x60 pixel square from the center, and then `strokeRect()` is called to create a rectangular outline 50x50 pixels within the cleared square (*conceptually* 50x50; in reality it's 52x52, as the next section will explain).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In upcoming pages we'll see two alternative methods for `clearRect()`, and we'll also see how to change the color and stroke style of the rendered shapes.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Unlike the path functions we'll see in the next section, all three rectangle functions draw immediately to the canvas.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In the rectangle example above, and in all the examples to come, you may notice that the shapes' edges may appear blurrier than the equivalent shapes drawn with SVG or CSS.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This is not because the canvas API is incapable of drawing sharp edges, but rather because of the way the canvas grid maps to the actual pixels on the screen, and also, in certain cases, because of how the browser scales the canvas.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In this example, we create our canvas really small (15x15), but then use CSS to scale it up to 300x300 pixels.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] As a result, each canvas pixel is now represented by a 20x20 block of CSS pixels.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] We draw a stroked rectangle from (2,2) to (12,12) and a filled rectangle from (7,7) to (8,8).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This is because by default, when the browser scales raster images, it uses a smoothing algorithm to interpolate the extra pixels.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This is great for photographs or canvas graphics with curly edges, but not so great for straight-edged shapes.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Now, when the browser scales the canvas, it preserves the pixelation of the original as much as possible.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] But now another issue becomes apparent, one that you can actually also observe in the original rectangle example: the stroked rectangle is not only 2 pixels wide instead of 1, but also appears gray rather than the default black.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This is because of how the coordinates are interpreted as shape boundaries.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] If you look at the grid diagram above again, you can see that coordinates like `2` or `12` do not identify a pixel, but rather the edge between two pixels.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In the images below, the grid represents the canvas coordinate grid.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The squares between grid lines are actual on-screen pixels.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In the first grid image below, a rectangle from (2,1) to (5,5) is filled.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The entire area between them (light red) falls on pixel boundaries, so the resulting filled rectangle will have crisp edges.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The grid lines are actual pixels on the screen.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The top left corner of each grid is labeled (0,0).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In the first grid, a rectangle from (2,1) to (5,5) is filled in light-red color.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In the second grid, (3,1) to (3,5) is joined with a 1-pixel thick royal blue line.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The royal-blue line is centered on a grid line, extends from 2.5 to 3.5 on the x access, halfway into the pixels on either side of the graph line, with a light blue background on either side extending from 2 to 4 on the x-access.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] To avoid the light blue blur extension of the line in the second coordinate grid, the path in, the third coordinate grid is a royal-blue from line (3.5,1) to (3.5,5).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] If you consider a path from (3,1) to (3,5) with a line thickness of `1.0`, you end up with the situation in the second image.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The actual area to be filled (dark blue) only extends halfway into the pixels on either side of the path.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] An approximation of this has to be rendered, which means that those pixels being only partially shaded, and results in the entire area (the light blue and dark blue) being filled in with a color only half as dark as the actual stroke color.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This is what happens with the `1.0` width line in the `strokeRect()` call in the rectangle example above.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] To fix this, you have to be very precise in your path creation.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Knowing that a `1.0` width line will extend half a unit to either side of the path, creating the path from *centers* of pixels results in the situation in the third image—the `1.0` line width ends up completely and precisely filling a single pixel vertical line.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] So this is why we said earlier that the `strokeRect(50, 50, 50, 50)` call in the rectangle example was *conceptually* 50x50, but in reality it is 52x52.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The actual filled region for the outline starts at (49.5, 49.5) and ends at (100.5, 100.5), and because of the partially filled pixels, the actually filled area is from (49,49) to (101,101), which is 52x52, and the edges are 2-pixel wide.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] For even-width lines, each half ends up being an integer amount of pixels, so you want a path that is between pixels (that is, (3,1) to (3,5)), instead of down the middle of pixels.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] While slightly painful when initially working with scalable 2D graphics, paying attention to the pixel grid and the position of paths ensures that your drawings will look correct regardless of scaling or any other transformations involved.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] A 1.0-width vertical line drawn at the correct position will become a crisp 2-pixel line when scaled up by 2, and will appear at the correct position.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This phenomenon of partially filled pixels also extends to shapes that don't align to the pixel grid.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] For example, consider a rotated rectangle (you'll learn about drawing it in the next section).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] If scaling *up* an image makes it appear blurrier than intended, then scaling *down* an image would make it appear *sharper*.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] For example, if you want a canvas to appear as 300x150 pixels on the screen, you can create it as 600x300 pixels and then use CSS to scale it down.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This is especially useful on high-DPI screens (such as Apple's Retina displays) where a CSS pixel is represented by multiple screen pixels, so if you faithfully paint a 300x150 pixel canvas, it will not have the same pixel resolution as other elements on the page.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] A path is a list of points, connected by segments of lines that can be of different shapes, curved or not, of different width and of different color.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] A path, or even a subpath, can be closed.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Then you use drawing commands to draw into the path.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Once the path has been created, you can stroke or fill the path to render it.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Once created, future drawing commands are directed into the path and used to build the path up.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Methods to set different paths for objects.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Adds a straight line to the path, going to the start of the current sub-path.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Draws the shape by stroking its outline.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Draws a solid shape by filling the path's content area.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The first step to create a path is to call the `beginPath()`.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Internally, paths are stored as a list of sub-paths (lines, arcs, etc.) which together form a shape.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Every time this method is called, the list is reset and we can start drawing new shapes.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The second step is calling the methods that actually specify the paths to be drawn.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The third, and an optional step, is to call `closePath()`.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This method tries to close the shape by drawing a straight line from the current point to the start.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] If the shape has already been closed or there's only one point in the list, this function does nothing.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] One very useful function, which doesn't actually draw anything but becomes part of the path list described above, is the `moveTo()` function.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] You can probably best think of this as lifting a pen or pencil from one spot on a piece of paper and placing it on the next.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Moves the pen to the coordinates specified by `x` and `y`.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] When the canvas is initialized or `beginPath()` is called, you typically will want to use the `moveTo()` function to place the starting point somewhere else.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] We could also use `moveTo()` to draw unconnected paths.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] To try this for yourself, you can use the code snippet below.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Just paste it into the `draw()` function we saw earlier.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] If you'd like to see the connecting lines, you can remove the lines that call `moveTo()`.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] For drawing straight lines, use the `lineTo()` method.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Draws a line from the current drawing position to the position specified by `x` and `y`.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This method takes two arguments, `x` and `y`, which are the coordinates of the line's end point.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The starting point is dependent on previously drawn paths, where the end point of the previous path is the starting point for the following, etc.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The starting point can also be changed by using the `moveTo()` method.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The example below draws two triangles, one filled and one outlined.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This starts by calling `beginPath()` to start a new shape path.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] We then use the `moveTo()` method to move the starting point to the desired position.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Below this, two lines are drawn which make up two sides of the triangle.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] You'll notice the difference between the filled and stroked triangle.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This is, as mentioned above, because shapes are automatically closed when a path is filled, but not when they are stroked.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] If we left out the `closePath()` for the stroked triangle, only two lines would have been drawn, not a complete triangle.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] To draw arcs or circles, we use the `arc()` or `arcTo()` methods.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Draws an arc which is centered at *(x, y)* position with radius *r* starting at *startAngle* and ending at *endAngle* going in the given direction indicated by *counterclockwise* (defaulting to clockwise).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Draws an arc with the given control points and radius, connected to the previous point by a straight line.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Let's have a more detailed look at the `arc` method, which takes six parameters: `x` and `y` are the coordinates of the center of the circle on which the arc should be drawn.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The `startAngle` and `endAngle` parameters define the start and end points of the arc in radians, along the curve of the circle.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The `counterclockwise` parameter is a Boolean value which, when `true`, draws the arc counterclockwise; otherwise, the arc is drawn clockwise.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The following example is a little more complex than the ones we've seen above.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] It draws 12 different arcs all with different angles and fills.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The two `for` loops are for looping through the rows and columns of arcs.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] For each arc, we start a new path by calling `beginPath()`.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In the code, each of the parameters for the arc is in a variable for clarity, but you wouldn't necessarily do that in real life.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The `x` and `y` coordinates should be clear enough.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The `endAngle` starts at 180 degrees (half a circle) in the first column and is increased by steps of 90 degrees, culminating in a complete circle in the last column.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The statement for the `clockwise` parameter results in the first and third row being drawn as clockwise arcs and the second and fourth row as counterclockwise arcs.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Finally, the `if` statement makes the top half stroked arcs and the bottom half filled arcs.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The next type of paths available are Bézier curves, available in both cubic and quadratic varieties.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] These are generally used to draw complex organic shapes.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Draws a quadratic Bézier curve from the current pen position to the end point specified by `x` and `y`, using the control point specified by `cp1x` and `cp1y`.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Draws a cubic Bézier curve from the current pen position to the end point specified by `x` and `y`, using the control points specified by (`cp1x`, `cp1y`) and (`cp2x`, `cp2y`).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The difference between these is that a quadratic Bézier curve has a start and an end point (blue dots) and just one **control point** (indicated by the red dot) while a cubic Bézier curve uses two control points.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The `x` and `y` parameters in both of these methods are the coordinates of the end point.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] `cp1x` and `cp1y` are the coordinates of the first control point, and `cp2x` and `cp2y` are the coordinates of the second control point.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Using quadratic and cubic Bézier curves can be quite challenging, because unlike vector drawing software like Adobe Illustrator, we don't have direct visual feedback as to what we're doing.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This makes it pretty hard to draw complex shapes.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In the following example, we'll be drawing some simple organic shapes, but if you have the time and, most of all, the patience, much more complex shapes can be created.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] There's nothing very difficult in these examples.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In both cases we see a succession of curves being drawn which finally result in a complete shape.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This example uses multiple quadratic Bézier curves to render a speech balloon.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This example draws a heart using cubic Bézier curves.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In addition to the three methods we saw in Drawing rectangles, which draw rectangular shapes directly to the canvas, there's also the `rect()` method, which adds a rectangular path to a currently open path.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Draws a rectangle whose top-left corner is specified by (`x`, `y`) with the specified `width` and `height`.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Before this method is executed, the `moveTo()` method is automatically called with the parameters (x,y).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In other words, the current pen position is automatically reset to the default coordinates.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] So far, each example on this page has used only one type of path function per shape.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] However, there's no limitation to the number or types of paths you can use to create a shape.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] So in this final example, let's combine all of the path functions to make a set of very famous game characters.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] We won't go over this in detail, since it's actually surprisingly simple.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The most important things to note are the use of the `fillStyle` property on the drawing context, and the use of a utility function (in this case `roundedRect()`).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Using utility functions for bits of drawing you do often can be very helpful and reduce the amount of code you need, as well as its complexity.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] We'll take another look at `fillStyle`, in more detail, later in this tutorial.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Here, all we're doing is using it to change the fill color for paths from the default color of black to white, and then back again.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] To draw a shape with a hole in it, we need to draw the hole in different clock directions as we draw the outer shape.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] We either draw the outer shape clockwise and the inner shape anticlockwise or the outer shape anticlockwise and the inner shape clockwise.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In the example above, the outer triangle goes clockwise (move to the top-left corner, then draw a line to the top-right corner, and finish at the bottom) and the inner triangle goes anticlockwise (move to the top, then line to the bottom-left corner, and finish at the bottom-right).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] As we have seen in the last example, there can be a series of paths and drawing commands to draw objects onto your canvas.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] To simplify the code and to improve performance, the `Path2D` object, available in recent versions of browsers, lets you cache or record these drawing commands.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] You are able to play back your paths quickly.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The **`Path2D()`** constructor returns a newly instantiated `Path2D` object, optionally with another path as an argument (creates a copy), or optionally with a string consisting of SVG path data.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] All path methods like `moveTo`, `rect`, `arc` or `quadraticCurveTo`, etc., which we got to know above, are available on `Path2D` objects.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The `Path2D` API also adds a way to combine paths using the `addPath` method.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This can be useful when you want to build objects from several components, for example.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Adds a path to the current path with an optional transformation matrix.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] In this example, we are creating a rectangle and a circle.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Both are stored as a `Path2D` object, so that they are available for later usage.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] With the new `Path2D` API, several methods got updated to optionally accept a `Path2D` object to use instead of the current path.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Here, `stroke` and `fill` are used with a path argument to draw both objects onto the canvas, for example.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] Another powerful feature of the new canvas `Path2D` API is using SVG path data to initialize paths on your canvas.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] This might allow you to pass around path data and re-use them in both, SVG and canvas.
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] The path will move to point (`M10 10`) and then move horizontally 80 points to the right (`h 80`), then 80 points down (`v 80`), then 80 points to the left (`h -80`), and then back to the start (`z`).
[src:canvas-api/drawing-shapes] You can see this example on the `Path2D` constructor page.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] It’s been available across browsers since March 2023.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] When using the `<canvas>` element or the Canvas API, rendering, animation, and user interaction usually happen on the main execution thread of a web application.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] The computation relating to canvas animations and rendering can have a significant impact on application performance.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] The **`OffscreenCanvas`** interface provides a canvas that can be rendered off screen, decoupling the DOM and the Canvas API so that the `<canvas>` element is no longer entirely dependent on the DOM.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] Rendering operations can also be run inside a worker context, allowing you to run some tasks in a separate thread and avoid heavy work on the main thread.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] `OffscreenCanvas` is a transferable object.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] Returns a drawing context for the offscreen canvas, or `null` if the context identifier is not supported, or the offscreen canvas has already been set to a different context mode.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] Creates a `Blob` object representing the image contained in the canvas.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] Creates an `ImageBitmap` object from the most recently rendered image of the `OffscreenCanvas`.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] See its reference for important notes on managing this `ImageBitmap`.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] Fired if the browser detects that an `OffscreenCanvasRenderingContext2D` context is lost.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] Fired if the browser successfully restores an `OffscreenCanvasRenderingContext2D` context.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] One way to use the `OffscreenCanvas` API is to use a rendering context that has been obtained from an `OffscreenCanvas` object to generate new frames.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] Once a new frame has finished rendering in this context, the `transferToImageBitmap()` method can be called to save the most recent rendered image.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] This method returns an `ImageBitmap` object, which can be used in a variety of Web APIs and also in a second canvas without creating a transfer copy.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] To display the `ImageBitmap`, you can use an `ImageBitmapRenderingContext` context, which can be created by calling `canvas.getContext("bitmaprenderer")` on a (visible) canvas element.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] This context only provides functionality to replace the canvas's contents with the given `ImageBitmap`.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] A call to `ImageBitmapRenderingContext.transferFromImageBitmap()` with the previously rendered and saved `ImageBitmap` from the OffscreenCanvas, will display the `ImageBitmap` on the canvas and transfer its ownership to the canvas.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] A single `OffscreenCanvas` may transfer frames into an arbitrary number of other `ImageBitmapRenderingContext` objects.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] the following code will provide the rendering using `OffscreenCanvas` as described above.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] Another way to use the `OffscreenCanvas` API, is to call `transferControlToOffscreen()` on a `<canvas>` element, either on a worker or the main thread, which will return an `OffscreenCanvas` object from an `HTMLCanvasElement` object from the main thread.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] Calling `getContext()` will then obtain a rendering context from that `OffscreenCanvas`.
[src:canvas-api/offscreencanvas] For a full example, see the OffscreenCanvas example source on GitHub or run the OffscreenCanvas example live.
